# Abstract Classes and Interfaces

## Abstract Classes — Partial Implementation
An abstract class defines a template: some methods are fully implemented (inherited as-is), others are declared abstract (subclasses must implement them). Abstract classes cannot be instantiated with `new`.

```java
public abstract class PaymentProcessor {
    // Concrete method — all processors share this logging
    protected void logTransaction(String txId, BigDecimal amount) {
        System.out.printf("TX %s: %s%n", txId, amount);
    }

    // Abstract method — each processor implements differently
    public abstract boolean process(BigDecimal amount, String currency);

    // Template method pattern — algorithm skeleton defined here
    public final boolean execute(BigDecimal amount, String currency) {
        logTransaction(UUID.randomUUID().toString(), amount);
        boolean result = process(amount, currency);
        if (!result) logTransaction("FAILED", amount);
        return result;
    }
}

public class StripeProcessor extends PaymentProcessor {
    @Override
    public boolean process(BigDecimal amount, String currency) {
        // Call Stripe API...
        return true;
    }
}
```
The `final execute()` method is the **Template Method Pattern** — the algorithm skeleton is fixed; only specific steps vary.

## Interfaces — Pure Contracts
An interface defines what an object can do, not how. Since Java 8, interfaces can have `default` and `static` methods with implementations.

```java
public interface Exportable {
    String toJson();          // abstract — implementing class MUST provide this
    String toCsv();

    default String toXml() { // default — optional to override
        return "<data>" + toJson() + "</data>";
    }

    static Exportable empty() { // static factory — called on the interface
        return new EmptyExportable();
    }
}

public class Report implements Exportable {
    @Override public String toJson() { return "{"report":true}"; }
    @Override public String toCsv()  { return "report,true"; }
    // toXml() is inherited from the interface default
}
```

## Abstract Class vs Interface — The Decision Matrix
| | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---|---|---|
| Purpose | Partial implementation + shared state | Pure contract (capability) |
| Fields | Yes (instance fields) | Only `public static final` constants |
| Constructor | Yes | No |
| Multiple | One (single inheritance) | Many (a class can implement multiple) |
| `default` methods | Available | Available (since Java 8) |
| Use when | Related classes share code AND state | Unrelated classes share a capability |

**The rule:** if it's an IS-A relationship with shared mutable state, use abstract class. If it's a CAN-DO capability (Serializable, Comparable, Runnable, AutoCloseable), use interface.

## Functional Interfaces — One Method, Enables Lambdas
A functional interface has exactly one abstract method. It can be implemented with a lambda:
```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Validator<T> {
    boolean validate(T value);
}

Validator<String> notEmpty = s -> !s.isBlank();
notEmpty.validate("hello"); // true
```
Built-in functional interfaces: `Predicate<T>`, `Function<T,R>`, `Consumer<T>`, `Supplier<T>` — all used in Java Streams (Day 36).

## Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Don't force implementers to implement methods they don't use. Split large interfaces into focused ones:
```java
// Bad: one large interface
interface CrudRepository { save(); findById(); delete(); exportToCsv(); emailReport(); }

// Good: segregated
interface CrudRepository { save(); findById(); delete(); }
interface Exportable { exportToCsv(); }
interface Reportable { emailReport(); }
```

## Connection to Spring Boot
Spring Boot is built entirely on interfaces and abstract classes:
- `JpaRepository<Entity, ID>` is an interface — you extend it to get 15+ methods for free.
- `WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter` (deprecated but common) was an abstract class.
- Every Spring bean can be declared by interface: `@Autowired private UserRepository repo;` — Spring injects the concrete implementation. This is the basis of dependency injection and mocking in tests.

## Common Mistakes
1. **Abstract class can have a constructor** — but it cannot be called with `new AbstractClass()`. It's called via `super()` from subclasses.
2. **Interface fields are implicitly `public static final`** — they are constants, not instance variables.
3. **Implementing interface with lambda** — only works for functional interfaces (single abstract method). Adding a second abstract method breaks lambda support.
4. **Confusing `default` method with abstract:** `default` provides an implementation; omitting `default` makes it abstract and required.

